  "text": "Critiquing these counter-intuitive findings of [CITATION_1] as due to weak econometric methodology, [CITATION_2] re-examine the impact of changes in the levels and volatility of capital flows on the Indian exchange rates. Their theoretical model specifies a goods market, money market, domestic bond market and a foreign assets market with a wealth identity connecting the latter three. Inflation is determined by the output gap but is also impacted by the exchange rate movements. Balance of trade and factor incomes equal the capital flows in a simple BOP identity. In the estimated reduced form equation REER is a function of level and volatility of real net capital flows, real government expenditure, real current account balance and money supply. For the period 1993Q2 to 2004Q1, [CITATION_3] obtain that the REER is positively related to real net capital inflows and their volatility. Net capital flows cause the REER to appreciate. These results are corroborated by [CITATION_4] .",
